om German <i>Wald</i> ‘forest’. Very few Jews would have been living anywhere near a forest at the time when they acquired surnames, so as a Jewish name its origins are unlikely to be topographic."]},{"name":"Waldon","meanings":["English: variant of   Walden  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Walden was born in 1410, in Europe as the daughter of Richard Walden and Mrs Richard Walden. She married John Cockett Esq before 1430, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1430, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1410–1430":"1410–1430","1405–1483":"1405–1483","1430–1502":"1430–1502","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1502":"1502","1410":"1410","before 1410":"enne 1410","before 1430":"enne 1430","1430":"1430","1483":"1483","1405":"1405","Ampton, Suffolk, England":"Ampton, Suffolk, England","Europe":"Europe","England":"England"},"fi":{"1410–1430":"1410–1430","1405–1483":"1405–1483","1430–1502":"1430–1502","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1502":"1502","1410":"1410","before 1410":"ennen vuotta 1410","before 1430":"ennen vuotta 1430","1430":"1430","1483":"1483","1405":"1405","Ampton, Suffolk, England":"Ampton, Suffolk, England","Europe":"Europe","England":"England"},"fr":{"1410–1430":"1410–1430","1405–1483":"1405–1483","1430–1502":"1430–1502","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1502":"1502","1410":"1410","before 1410":"avant 1410","before 1430":"avant 1430","1430":"1430","1483":"1483","1405":"1405","Ampton, Suffolk, England":"Ampton, Suffolk, Angleterre","Europe":"Europe","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret Walden est née en 1410, à Europe, fille de Richard Walden et Mrs Richard Walden. Elle a épousé John Cockett Esq avant 1430, 